{
  "doc_id": "15231",
  "text": "Effective pain management for severely burned victims can be problematic. [CITATION_1] During the early emergent phase, potent opioids such as morphine sulfate, hydromorphone and fentanyl should be given intravenously and titrated based on patient response. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] For moderate pain, an oral oxycodone/acetaminophen mixture may be used while oral non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs and acetaminophen can be administered for minor pain. [CITATION_4] Antidepressants, anticonvulsants, and antianxiety agents have also been found to be useful adjuvants in pain management of burn patients. [CITATION_5] Ketamine, at sub-dissociative doses of 0.1-0.2 mg/kg can be given intravenously, especially in patients who are resistant to large doses of opioids.",
